                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d565">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93/1762: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-11T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >April 11, 1944—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 10:01 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>631. Consul [at] Tihwa reports in telegram April 6 following information obtained
                    from Foreign Affairs Delegate (Embassy’s 613, April 6):</p>
                <p>Six hundred Kazaks attacked Sinkiang caravan during night April 4 at point south
                    of Fuwen located 60 kilometers this side of Mongol-Soviet border.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
